						<h3><a href="#!">Is there progress? Indicators and targets</a></h3>
						<div> 
								<!--*********************************PURPLE HEADER*********************************-->
								<div class="purpBarHeader">What is the indicator? </div>
								<p>Although shoreline armoring is one of the indicators that measure the pressures on Puget Sound, rather than a measure of the state of the ecosystem such as the biomass of Pacific herring, it is an important indicator of ecological conditions in Puget Sound.</p>
								<p>Shoreline armoring is the most common type of shoreline modification on Puget Sound. Armoring directly alters geologic processes that build and maintain beaches and spits. Bulkheads also impact erosion patterns on nearby beaches, alter beach substrate and hydrology, and reduce the availability of large wood.</p><p>
										These physical changes to beaches can diminish the availability and condition of key shoreline habitats. Armoring can also directly impact organisms and ecological processes by burying or displacing upper beach habitat and altering the natural transition between terrestrial and aquatic ecosystems. Impacts of armoring differ from one coastal setting to another, but have been demonstrated both on Puget Sound and elsewhere to impact habitat for fish, birds, and invertebrates.</p>
								<p>Because of these adverse impacts on coastal processes and shoreline habitat, the goal is to decrease the amount of new armoring that occurs on Puget Sound, while also seeking opportunities to reduce armoring where feasible.</p>
								<p>As new armoring is being constructed, concurrent efforts are deployed to remove armoring primarily for habitat restoration. Thus, it is the difference between new and removed armoring that is of interest to address the target specifically, reported here as the net amount of shoreline armoring. To reach the target, there has to be a net loss of armoring cumulatively over 2011 to 2020.</p>
								<p>Alterations to the shoreline are regulated primarily by two state laws, the Shoreline Management Act and the Hydraulic Code. Under the Hydraulic Code, project proponents seeking a permit for in-water and shoreline construction activities declare the amount of armoring they plan on adding, replacing, or removing in their application. Thus, data reported here were compiled from Hydraulic Project Approvals (HPAs) issued from January 2005 through December 2012 by the Washington Department of Fish &amp; Wildlife.</p>
								<p>Projects were identified as:</p>
								<ol>
										<li>New (previously unarmored shoreline)</li>
										<li>Replacement (complete replacement of existing armoring)</li>
										<li>Removals (removal of existing armoring without replacement)								</li>
								</ol>
								<p>The Puget Sound Nearshore Ecosystem Restoration Project (PSNERP) has been instrumental in compiling and reporting on changes to shorelines in Puget Sound over the past several decades. We relied on their data to report the length of shoreline and the overall amount of existing shoreline armoring in Puget Sound.</p>

								<!--*********************************PURPLE HEADER*********************************-->
								<div class="purpBarHeader">What are the targets? </div>
								<h5>2020 target</h5>
								<p>Part 1: From 2011 to 2020, the total amount of armoring removed should be greater than the total amount of new armoring in Puget Sound (total miles removed is greater than the total miles added).<br />
										Part 2: Feeder bluffs receive strategic attention for removal of existing armoring and avoidance of new armoring.<br />
								Part 3: Soft shore techniques are used for all new and replacement armoring, unless it is demonstrably infeasible.</p>
<h5>Interim targets</h5>
								<p>There currently are no interim targets for this Vital Sign.</p>
								<h5>&nbsp;</h5>
								<!--*********************************PURPLE HEADER*********************************-->
								<div class="purpBarHeader">Is there progress? </div>
                                <p>No progress was made with the shoreline armoring indicator. The net change in length of shoreline armoring (new armoring minus removed armoring) was 6.9 miles between 2005 and 2012. This value is further away from the target than before (i.e., greater than the baseline reference), and thus the indicator is losing ground. The amount of new shoreline armoring in Puget Sound was substantially greater than the amount removed for every year from 2005 through 2012. New shoreline armoring continues to be constructed each year at an average pace of 1.0 miles per year. Shoreline armoring is removed at an average pace of 0.2 miles per year.<br />
In 2012 alone, the latest year with available data, permits were issued for a total of 1.1 miles of new armoring. Permits were also issued to remove a total of 0.7 miles of existing armoring resulting in a net of 0.4 miles of shoreline armoring. This was the highest level of removal over the eight years of data and resulted in the lowest level of net new armoring for all years from 2005-2012.While this pattern still results in additional new armoring, and is not consistent with the 2020 target, it is a substantial improvement over the previous seven years where net armoring averaged 0.9 miles per year.</p>
								<p>Although there has been an incremental increase in removal of armoring since 2005, permits issued for new armoring construction were substantially higher in 2006 and 2007, declined significantly in 2008, and displayed modest increases from 2010 to 2012. Unfortunately, the increase in permits for new installations in 2012 dampened the effect of the substantial upsurge in removals that same year.</p>
								<p>Although more armoring has been removed in recent years (e.g., 2008-2012), it will take significant progress on both: a) decreasing the amount of new armoring and b) increasing the amount of removed armoring to reverse the current trend and meet the target by 2020. If the trend of adding and removing armoring exhibited by the data for 2005 through 2012 continues, an additional 7.2 miles of new armoring will be added to Puget Sound shorelines between 2012 and 2020, making it unlikely that the 2020 target will be met. However, if the improved condition shown in 2012 is continued, a total of 3.4 miles of new armoring would be added by 2020.</p>
								<p><strong>Part 2: </strong><strong>Feeder bluffs receive strategic attention for removal of existing armoring and avoidance of new armoring.</strong></p>
								<p>Part of the 2020 target for shoreline armoring includes a focus on preventing new armoring and reducing existing armoring on feeder bluffs that supply sediments to Puget Sound shorelines. Ecology completed a project in 2014 to map feeder bluffs throughout Puget Sound. This will improve our ability to identify where new armoring is proposed on feeder bluffs and to better quantify the extent to which this occurs.  Increasingly, local regulations specifically discourage armoring on feeder bluffs.</p>
								<p><strong>Part 3: Soft shore techniques are used for all new and replacement armoring, unless it is demonstrably infeasible.</strong></p>
								<p>The 2020 target emphasizes the increased use of softer techniques for both new and replacement armoring. The new Hydraulic Code (Chapter 220-660 WAC) effective on July 1, 2015 defines soft shore techniques. Beginning at that time, HPAs issued for armoring should include specifics regarding use of these techniques. From that point on, we should be able to query the database for information on how much is being installed, where it is being installed, how it is being installed (new or replacement work) and who is installing it (residential applications, public facilities, etc.).</p>
								<p>The Washington State Department of Ecology has recently developed<a href="https://fortress.wa.gov/ecy/publications/publications/1406009.pdf" target="new"> guidance for local communities</a> trying to implement softer techniques through their Shoreline Master Programs (Gianou 2014). In 2014, WDFW published the<a href="http://wdfw.wa.gov/publications/01583/" target="new"> Marine Shoreline Design Guidelines</a>, offering new guidance on design and construction of softer measures (Johannessen et al. 2014). Together, we expect the guidance to lead to even greater use of soft methods of shoreline stabilization. </p>
								<p>Citations:<br />
										Gianou, K. 2014. Soft Shoreline Stabilization: Shoreline Master Program Planning and Implementation Guidance. Shorelands and Environmental Assistance Program, Washington Department of Ecology, Olympia, WA. Publication no. 14-06-009.</p>
								<p>Johannessen, J., A. MacLennan, A. Blue, J. Waggoner, S. Williams, W. Gerstel, R. Barnard, R. Carman, and H. Shipman, 2014. Marine Shoreline Design Guidelines. Washington Department of Fish and Wildlife, Olympia, Washington.</p>
