						<!--*********************************FOLD 03*********************************-->
						<h3><a href="#!">Latest data and maps</a></h3>
						<div> 
								<!--*********************************PURPLE HEADER*********************************-->
								<div class="purpBarHeader">Data</div>
								<img src="images/vs12_shoreline_summary.jpg" width="600" height="553" alt="Puget Sound Shoreline Armoring 2005-2011" />
<p>Based on a compilation of a variety of data sources by PSNERP, 27% of the shoreline of Puget Sound is armored (666 miles). A total of 1,201 Hydraulic Project Approvals (HPAs) were issued for shoreline armoring projects (including permits for new, replaced and removed armoring) in Puget Sound from January 2005 through December 2012. In each year, the amount of new armoring (on average 1.0 mile per year) substantially exceeded the amount removed (on average 0.2 miles per year). As a result, a positive balance of additional armoring in Puget Sound has been accumulating, for a net total of 6.9 miles (on average, 0.9 miles of additional armoring per year). In addition, the amount of replaced armoring greatly exceeded either new or removed armoring during every year in the same time period. Overall, permit approvals were issued for 8.3 miles of new shoreline armor, 1.4 miles of armor removal, and 17.5 miles of replacement armor between 2005 and 2012. There were no statistically significant linear trends in the amount of new or replacement armoring permitted through the eight-year period.</p><p>
		In 2012 alone, the last year for which data were available, permits were issued for 1.1 miles of new armoring, 1.6 times more than permits for armoring removal (0.7 miles). The rates of adding armoring has generally been relatively constant in the last 5 years of available data. The amount of removed armoring has increased incrementally over the same period, albeit at a very small fraction of new armoring. It is noteworthy that the amount of removed armoring increased substantially in 2012 (more than tripled relative to all previous years).</p>
<p><img src="images/vs12_shoreline_newandremovedpie.jpg" width="800" height="339" alt=""/></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The type of applicant that conducts new or armor removal projects was also compiled from the HPA data for years 2005-2012. Armoring is particularly extensive in highly developed residential, urban, or industrial centers. While most alterations to nearshore areas are heavily regulated, new and replacement shoreline armoring is still relatively commonplace for single-family residences. Single-family residences accounted for 68 percent of the HPA applicants requesting to construct new armoring between 2005 and 2012. In contrast, armor removal projects were primarily conducted on government properties (57%), whereas only 11% of the removals were on single-family residential properties.</p>

<p><img src="images/vs12_shoreline_bycountypie.jpg" width="500" height="386" alt=""/></p>
<p>The total amount of existing shoreline armoring varies considerably across the 12 counties that border Puget Sound. Three counties account for nearly 50% of the total existing armoring in Puget Sound: King (13%), Pierce (18%), and Kitsap (16%) counties. In these same three counties, the proportion of shoreline that is armored is relatively high: King 73%, Pierce 51%, and Kitsap 43%. New armoring was constructed in all 12 counties. However, the HPA data revealed that most of the new armoring permitted between 2005-2012 was concentrated in somewhat different areas. Most of the new armoring was constructed in Mason, Island and Kitsap counties, comprising together 48% of the total. Pierce, Skagit and San Juan counties also accounted for a substantial amount of the new armoring with a combined total of 35%. Therefore, six of the 12 counties in Puget Sound accounted for 83% of the new armoring permitted from 2005 through 2012.</p>
<p>The same dataset indicates that armoring was removed in ten counties from 2005-2012. More armoring was removed in Kitsap County, totaling 0.7 miles, than in any other county during this eight year timeframe. A combined total of 0.5 miles was removed among four other counties that included King, Pierce, Mason and Island.  Clallam and Snohomish counties did not account for any armor removal during this period.</p>
<p>Also noteworthy for the 2005-2012 time period is the comparatively low amount of new armor permitted in King County (0.1 miles, or 582 feet), coupled with a relatively high quantity of removals (0.1 miles, or 553 feet), resulting in less than 0.01 miles, or only 29 feet, of net new armor.</p>
<p><strong>Why is this happening?</strong></p>
<p>While the amount of new armor permitted between 2011 and 2012 increased slightly, the amount of armor removed was up substantially. A continued positive trend in removals, which has occurred since 2005 albeit at a smaller level, is likely associated with both: 1) an increased awareness of the impacts to shoreline functions caused by armor, and 2) the efforts by restoration groups to address the problem by seeking potential removal opportunities.</p>
<p>New armor, however, continues to be constructed at the rate of about one mile per year. This apparent contradiction is in part because the situations where new armoring is occurring are quite different than those where it is being removed.&nbsp; New armoring is driven by a perception of risk –sometimes a very real risk – to property and safety. New armoring may occur following severe storms and landslides and may be dealt with as an emergency, not receiving the scrutiny normally applied to such projects. Shorelines are inherently unstable.&nbsp;Much new armoring is likely occurring on properties that were laid out or developed decades ago, without sufficient attention to erosion and flood hazards.</p>
<p>On the positive side, restoration groups appear to have become increasingly successful at obtaining funding from restoration grant programs for armor removal projects as indicated by both the scale and number of removals in recent years. In addition, public facilities such as state and county parks have become a large component of the armor removal trend. </p>
<p>Grant funds have also contributed to increased outreach to shoreline property owners, agency staff, contractors and others who have an interest in the condition of Puget Sound shorelines. Recent studies have provided demographic information on shoreline property owners to facilitate outreach activities that resonate with these owners who have considerable influence on shoreline activities. In addition, local governments on Puget Sound are in the process of updating Shoreline Master Programs in accordance with the new state guidelines.  We expect these to reduce the amount of armoring in the future, but our current data do not reflect the potential effect of these new SMPs.  We will be looking at the data over the next few years to see if we can detect a change in armoring trends in jurisdictions with updated SMPs.</p>
